From this point what remains of the book is con- cerned with the question of merit and grace If all a man has is lent to him, his merit is not his own; how can he then deserve any reward? In an earlier place Wycliffe had asserted, in forgetfulness of the emphatic declaration of Bradwardine to the con- trary2, that ‘no one denies that the creature can deserve of congruity as touching grace 3.’ He now argues the matter at length.
